4","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1005":"1005","1047":"1047","1057":"1057","1024":"1024","1023":"1023","about 1020":"circa 1020","Thorngate Castle, Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1020–":"about 1020–Deceased","1020–Female":"1020–Deceased","1021–1047":"1021–1047","1023–1074":"1023–1074","1023–1087":"1023–1087","1024–Male":"1024–Deceased","1030–1080":"1030–1080","1057–1129":"1057–1129","1063–Male":"1063–Deceased","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1005–Female":"1005–Deceased","1080":"1080","about 1063":"about 1063","1000":"1000","1087":"1087","1021":"1021","1020":"1020","1063":"1063","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1005":"1005","1047":"1047","1057":"1057","1024":"1024","1023":"1023","about 1020":"about 1020","Thorngate Castle, Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crispin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."],"variants":[{"name":"Crisp","meanings":["English: nickname for a man with curly hair, from Middle English <i>crisp</i>, <i>crips</i>, <i>scrip</i>, Old English <i>crisp</i>, <i>cryps</i> (from Latin <i>crispus</i>), reinforced in Middle English by an Old French word also from Latin <i>crispus</i>. In some cases this is possibly a nickname from the personal name   Crispin  .","Americanized form of German <b>Krisp</b>: nickname from Middle High German <i>krisp</i>, <i>krispel</i> ‘curly-haired man’.","Americanized form of German <b>Krisp</b>: from a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Krispin</i> (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crippen","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crespin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Raul, Vidal, Adelina, Alfonso, Amador, Andres, Aniceto, Delfino, Emilio.","Spanish (<b>Crespín</b>): variant of   Crispin  .","French: from the Latin personal name <i>Crispinus</i> (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crispen","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of German <b>Krispin</b>, a cognate of   Crispin  ."]},{"name":"Crispino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Luigi, Carlo, Amato, Angelo, Antonio, Domenico, Fiore, Gennaro, Michelina, Rocco, Sal, Salvator.","Italian (southern): from the personal name <i>Crispino</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, a derivative of the old Roman surname <i>Crispus</i> ‘curly(-headed)’ (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crippin","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crespi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jaime, Juan, Mercedes, Racquel, Alberto, Alejandro, Consuelo, Eduardo, Jose, Jose Manuel, Migdalia, Pedro.  Jewish Aron, Nissim.","Catalan (<b>Crespí</b>): from a personal name, the Catalan equivalent of   Crispin  .","Italian (northern): variant of   Crespo  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma Crispin was born about 1020, in France, her father, Gilbert Crispin, was 21 and her mother, Gunnora, was 17. She married Pierre de Condé. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1020–":"umbes 1020–Surnud","1020–Female":"1020–Surnud","1021–1047":"1021–1047","1023–1074":"1023–1074","1023–1087":"1023–1087","1024–Male":"1024–Surnud","1030–1080":"1030–1080","1057–1129":"1057–1129","1063–Male":"1063–Surnud","1000–1060":"1000–1060","1005–Female":"1005–Surnud","1080":"1080","about 1063":"umbes 1063","1000":"1000","1087":"1087","1021":"1021","1020":"1020","1063":"1063","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1005":"1005","1047":"1047","1057":"1057","1024":"1024","1023":"1023","about 1020":"umbes 1020","Thorngate Castle, Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1020–":"no